Parliament did not support an amendment to release Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning the opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the former prime minister's release from prison, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic offences at second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing a disadvantageous deal with Russia on the purchase of natural gas for Ukraine.
The verdict is not yet final, the appeals court has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge by the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Penal Code with which the former prime minister was convicted was supported by 147 MPs in the vote.
226 votes were needed for its approval.
