Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner sausages
More than one third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, with overweight affecting 9% of the school population and obesity affecting 5%.
Obese children are mostly from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, according to current research.
It is again demonstrated how important the environment in which one grows is for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obese children eat, for example, sausages at least twice as often as children from normal-weight families.
For dinner, more than 19 percent of the obese had eaten fries the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not an accident".
In families with overweight children, there is no practice of playing sports, which is true of most families today, where only 15% of children said that their parents find time for physical exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 children in Primary Education from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second edition of the program "Obesity Is Not an Accident", sponsored by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand children from 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
Proper diet and adequate family exercise are key factors in significantly reducing the number of overweight and even obese children.
"Only half of the children surveyed said that they eat five meals a day according to the diet: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet", says one of the survey results.
No breakfast but with dinner stuffing
Specialists warn that in healthy development, details are also important, such as having a set time for family breakfast.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of schoolchildren's families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to discover that in 10% of households, they don't have breakfast.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a proper daily diet.
The study shows that families with obese children are much more likely to eat the insane fries.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweets daily (70%).
Over 40% of children surveyed are normally involved in sport, but among their parents this figure is less than half, only 15%.
Make your own diet
The next phase of the study enabled the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all the possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The food preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from ideal from the point of view of healthy eating".
Their favorite foods include pasta, meat, and sweets
"The popularity of soft drinks is particularly alarming", warns the final report of the study.
The main meal is the palm-tree pasta and closely followed by the poultry.
Children almost always reject legumes and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Changing to Healthy Habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they are given the right information.
"In the control group of study participants, who completed the questionnaire after finishing the prevention programme 'Obesity is not an accident', there was in many cases an important change in favour of the principles of a healthy diet", the study results point out.
The issue of soft drinks, for example, is of interest, as many children would begin to prefer regular water.
Children would also be more likely to choose poultry and fish as the main meal on the questionnaire and would restrict the consumption of sweet foods and flour derivatives.
The stylist must also be a good psychologist, the professionals argue
In the introductory article, How Stylists Learn, I already complained a little bit that the initial lessons were already quite loaded.
I had no idea how that was gonna go.
Three industry professionals' lectures, how to dress problem characters, and, in addition, a seminar on how it works in the entertainment world.
And it will get worse.
The closer the final exams, the more information and practical tasks await us
And although the course is held every Saturday and Sunday, there is no more pin for it.
We've once studied with the principal, Alena, (in the course there is no man) about how to dress the woman who doesn't have a perfect symmetry.
And so is the vast majority.
Someone is short, someone has a stylized figure without the right curves and someone is overweight.
The stylist must be able to smooth wide shoulders, lengthen a neck or recreate the necessary curves
We've been given certain tricks on how to make the body of a woman like Jennifer Lopez stand out, with huge breasts and hips but a tight waist and at the same time not dress her in a way that is too challenging.
If, for example, the gap between your waist and hips is so large that the skirt or pants do not fit, it is worth sewing at least one extra piece of fabric to your size.
You will not regret it, for clothes that fit perfectly are priceless.
A tailored skirt will feel much better than one that keeps moving, getting up, dancing around the waist, etc.
The stylized body can be allowed to wear clothes with folds, embroidery, embroidery or drape.
There are certainly many different kinds of information and bodies, so I'm glad I have all week to put all this information in my head.
And even so, I'm afraid with the assignment, I've got more than enough.
Each participant in the course has been assigned two celebrities, who will have to design two dressing rooms: one for the day and one for the night.
You have to consider the current look, the fashion style that suits the person in question.
I've got Miranda Kerr dressed up, you may know her from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
I scream inside, for me it's much better than, for example, Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, who has recently gained about a hundred kilos (please note the exaggeration), or the very young Selena Gomez.
We have to cut the dresses out of magazines or search the Internet and print them out, and then graphically elaborate them.
The moodboard, which is what the complete result is called, also expresses our personal style and our relationship with graphic design.
It is also important to think about the graphic part of the styling.
The stylist, therefore, not only dresses physically, but also deals, for example, with the product pages in magazines (of specific subjects, such as trends, bags, coats, etc.).
The designer Mario Kameník told us about all this.
But all this is for Sunday.
The stylist has to have a global vision.
The three special guest lecturers animated Saturday's lecture with information on all types of bodies.
The stylist Honza Pokorný, the fashion designer Jakub Polanka and the fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and the stylist should know how to take advantage of it.
And a good stylist knows how to work with the same garment in different ways.
Variability is, in this case, fundamental.
Thus, the gabarina (or trench-coat) can be worn classically with jeans and a T-shirt, but it also serves to dress the naked body in high heels and photograph it as if it were actually a dress.
Or you just wrap it up and put it up your neck to get a totally different image.
"Play with it", he insisted.
What I value most is the following advice: "To get started, you must first know all the rules".
"Then you can break them", Jakub said.
It's finally clear to me why we memorize all these formulas, what goes with what, why, if then it turns out that in fashion magazines we find different results.
Not to mention the parades.
Thanks to photographer Ben, I know a stylist has to have more types of clothes in the stock than he's planning to photograph.
So, for a fashion story that has ten pages (therefore, ten outfits), you have to have ready, ready to wear, at least fifteen.
And that in addition to the photos the clothes work in combination with other garments, all of which are different from what they are actually wearing.
All of this has to be taken into account when designing the outfit.
Honza Pokorný assured us that image and style alone are, in many cases, half of the success.
Just look at Madonna, who's not exactly an extraordinary singer, but the image and the marketing have made her a global star.
In the Czech Republic, at the moment, there is still no clear trend towards using the services of stylists.
Even famous people find it useless (my skills are enough, my physical appearance is not that important).
And when someone asks for our services, we have to keep in mind that it is very likely that they will tell us a size very different from their actual (smaller) size.
Then you just have to google and find out if the heart magazines have already written about it, if a certain celebrity has gained weight/fat etc.
On Sunday, Honza and Mario insisted that the stylist does not just orient himself in fashion, but also understands outfit.
During your work, you must communicate primarily with the people you see, so it is essential to be a good psychologist.
He knows how to value people, he doesn't miss them, he defends their opinions.
"When a director hires you to sort out her wardrobe and complete it with beautiful clothes, you can't just take everything and throw it away and say, 'Oh, what a horror.'"
"Find at least a couple of things you can think about and recommend so that someone can put them on", says Mario.
He himself also showed us that everything should fit into the so-called "placovka", that is, the work bag.
This is attached around the waist and all the necessary tools are there.
There are also nylon thread (which serves the stylist during the photo shoot of products such as bags or hats), special garment-hook pins in front, if this is larger (pins and other hooks are not allowed, as they could damage the fabric), or a sewing kit.
To avoid sitting around and doing something, we've learned to put on the soles of our shoes.
Even during the photo shoots in the studio, on a flat surface, the sole could be damaged and much more so the exterior.
And we just dressed and dressed.
We couldn't touch the shoes with the scissors so we wouldn't accidentally damage them.
So you had to be very clever.
Mario has given me a joy by praising my work without reservation.
I'm not really good at those skills.
This is just a small part of what we've been hearing all weekend, in the second part of the course.
I've realized that going into styling professionally is not a straightforward path, but I don't care what people say.
In Need for Speed: The Run, you race all over America.
The review
A journey, initially carefree, is complicated by a series of improper carelessness of a routine journey during the morning shift.
The Commission has not yet decided on the proposal for a regulation on the protection of the environment.
The new installment, to which The Run is added to the title, aroused great expectations even before its premiere.
It promised to give new airs to the old racing saga Need for Speed and, in the wake of what was shown, it appears as a game that should not end up being a mere action genre again.
We were also curious to see what the inserted scenes would look like, where the main character gets out of the car and walks on his own foot.
As is often the case in NFS series, the results do not vary much from what we expected.
There are races that can be considered acceptable, but in the total count points are lost because of absurd failures, which have been appearing in the series for years.
In reality, they cannot even be called errors, but rather the incomprehensible reluctance of programmers.
The adventure starts off really well.
You are introduced to a story, whose protagonist, Jack, has certain personal problems; to solve them, he is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You're sitting behind the wheel on the West Coast in San Francisco, and your mission is to get to New York first.
The idea is to offer something interesting.
The route is divided into ten stages and then over fifty races.
This means that each race takes place on a different route and the stages are located in different environments, which are quite diverse and interesting.
Thus, one does not have the slightest sense that the game always offers the same thing.
Some of the environments are even pleasing to the eye, although the technical level of the graphics is equivalent to that of previous installments of the series.
So it's not like it's from another world.
But a walk in the desert, the autumn landscape, or the high snow-capped mountains produce a very pleasant visual effect.
In addition, the races are occasionally diversified by an atypical element.
So, for example, in the desert you encounter a sandstorm that reduces visibility.
But in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get caught in an avalanche.
According to that, each of the races is very well developed.
There's only a couple of models, but that's enough.
For a moment, you try to overtake a demanding number of rivals (normal in a classic race), then you try to gain time (classic timed duel) and then a duel with a single opponent awaits you.
In the midst of all this, the police sometimes appear, which only makes things even more difficult.
The new thing is the scenery outside the car.
Interactive animations are presented when Jack, in most cases, has to escape from someone and you have to help him, always pressing the right button at the right time.
It's not complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are quite a few scenery in the game than one might expect (there are only three in particular).
But the end result is positive, because this element does not become annoying and, in the context already mentioned, is one of the elements that make the game more interesting.
The driving pattern follows the trail of the previous episodes.
That means that today it is not a big deal, but it cannot be said to be bad.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you can look elsewhere.
But a race designed with a lot of action is quite suited to this style of driving, although we may find something better among the competitive games.
So far, all in order.
But problems arise after a certain time.
Unlike the correct driving patterns, the same is no longer true of collisions.
Games like this can't be expected to recreate complicated warping and collisions, but in fact, before a hit on any object, you can't predict how your car will react, so not everything is in order.
Typically, when you overtake very tightly or drive in normal traffic, you will only see slight abrasions, but in other almost identical situations, your car will end up doing uncontrollable stunts.
Or even completely destroyed.
Thanks to the reset system, no big problems arise, but it can make you feel bad.
Rescue is programmed in such a way that when you get into an accident or you leave the track, the game returns you to the last rescue point on the track.
However, only five resets are available in each race.
If you consume them all, you have to restart the race from the beginning.
So it's just a help in case something goes wrong, but it's not very reliable.
Sometimes, even resetting doesn't help, it just helps to learn the given stage by heart.
One big disadvantage of the game is that the same events are repeated in different places.
In some corners, for example, you have to enter in a specific way; otherwise, they are impossible to take.
Other times you find yourself somewhere in "civil" vehicles always with the same configuration, even if you are first, fifth or arrive five minutes earlier or later.
This is especially rampant in situations, when you see two cars going to meet in opposite directions, your opponent advances without problems, but when you arrive, you must turn or brake.
It doesn't matter when you arrive, because it's programmed so that the "surprise" will always happen right in front of your nose.
The opponents have one more advantage.
Throughout the game, you'll arrive at places where, regardless of the moment, you'll always be overtaken by the same opponent in the same place.
And this happens at the end of the game, on a long bridge, which is even more shocking.
Your opponent must arrive before you, at any cost.
When it's in front of you, it makes it hard to see the cars coming in front of you, so you can start by looking at the car.
You can understand the idea of creating a game with maximum doses of suspense and adrenaline, but the execution is so obvious that you're probably disappointed right away.
And it's a shame, because even though the model of the journey is simple, the game is fun and action-packed, so it's often not possible to follow in detail what's happening or where.
And it really doesn't matter, whether the credit goes to the idea with fifty exclusive tracks or the qualifying in the race so it doesn't fit the boredom, or whatever.
An unusual idea is changing cars during races.
You have to be careful with the gas stations on the side of the road, because that's where you have to change cars, although in the vast majority of cases you'll be satisfied with what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, American muscle cars for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical driving, for example on curvy mountain roads.
In addition to the main narrative thread, there is also a parallel challenge thread, which means there are races in specific places that you will know from the stories.
Here you will get not only medals, but also experience points for your profile, which is useful for both challenges and stories.
When reaching the top level, the driver is opened up to several possibilities, starting with the car and ending with funds for the profile.
At the same time, an online Autolog function is connected, which compares your results with those of other players and provides other community functions.
One of the hardest elements to understand is how the last race in history is made.
You drive to the subway tunnel (pass), where you run in the dark along the tracks (pass).
The speedometer marks you between 150 and 200 km/h (pass) and, suddenly, the subway convoy comes behind you and takes you ahead without further ado.
We'll probably have a discussion in the newsroom about this for several days, about whether during the game programming no one thought even a little or whether the authors really think we're a bunch of fools.
The technical part of the game is not at all extraordinary, but at least the overall visual effects result in most cases pleasant, sometimes even superb.
It is a pity that in the most tense moments the quality of the image is reduced, and sometimes seriously.
This is particularly true of accidents involving many participants, when continuous image quality is no longer valid.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In order to appeal to the majority of the youth group, the soundtrack belongs to the category "each one of his father and mother", but one can assume that no one would buy the game just for its music.
The final feel of Need for Speed: The Run is therefore quite confusing.
If the game avoided absolutely silly mistakes, we'd have trouble claiming that The Run is the best NFS game in years.
It feels like the game isn't over.
The fun is assured, but be prepared because mistakes will hit you in the eye with the force of airport headlights.
The choirs of the University of Carolina will participate in the "Students of Velvet" concert.
The joint celebration of the International Students' Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution as a musical experience will take place for the third time at the Festa Academica festival.
During the event, twenty high school and university choirs will be featured.
The festival revolves around two concerts on November 17.
"Carolina University has a high turnout in the festival".
The choirs at the Faculty of Pedagogy and the Faculty of Humanities are among the current choirs, and the festival committee includes the rector Václav Hampl", said the organization's head, Jakub Čaloun.
The highlight of the festival is the free entry for all attendees to the high school choir concert, which will be held on March 17 at 2 p.m. in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program features the participation of Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička and his Celebration Jazz Mass.
In the evening, the concert "Students of Velvet" will be held at the Municipal House in Vynohrady, with the participation of university choirs, including the choir of the Carolina University.
The Festa Academica aims not only to celebrate the International Students' Day and commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music to the public at the highest level and to promote collaborative creation among young people.
The main organizer is the Czech Coral Union in collaboration with the Jan Kepler Secondary School.
All the events were supported by the mayor of Prague, Bohuslav Svoboda, and the rector of the Carolina University, Václav Hampl.
The Festival will take place between 16 and 20 November between Prague and Pardubice.
The calendar offers, in addition to the celebration concerts, a whole series of musical events, improvised student shows and morning concerts.
More information can be found on the festival's website www.festaacademica.cz
The EU Ambassador to the EU, Vicenová, said:
The Czechs have a reputation for being negative and Eurosceptic.
'The Lisbon Treaty has significantly affected the balance between individual institutions'
"I didn't expect a war to be waged without a barracks".
"It will take five or six years before the situation stabilizes a little, calms down and the new players get used to their new roles", Czech Ambassador to the EU Milena Vicenová began her lecture at the Faculty of Law with conviction.
How can we not take seriously his slogan 'clear and open about Europe', which he said at the beginning of his lecture, when he described each EU body and its relations with such precision and clarity that he would be the envy of many lecturers at the U.C. Law School.
Vicenová also weighed in on the work of the new permanent President of the European Council, Herman van Rompuy:
"The first thing that comes up is the criticism that if he is a gray-haired official, he can take on any role, but I have to say that he left everyone baffled, because he takes on his roles perfectly".
'He is a man who knows how to listen to the 27 Member States, communicate with them and has a clear vision of where the EU should go.'
The new post of Foreign and Security Policy Representative is explained by the question: 'Who is this EU? What number can I call it?' It is therefore an important step towards unification and clarification of the political union in the face of states like China or India.
No one wants to ban us from Olomouc cheese
Vicenová has also dealt with the agenda of the European Council in the near future.
The Czech presidency two years ago was a success.
The Czechs took care of the emerging economic crisis, resolved the gas crisis and organized a summit for the Eastern Partnership.
The fall of the government at that time was identified as a very negative aspect, which seriously affected the Czech Republic.
The Czech representation in the EU has many commitments at the moment.
In the words of the ambassador, "a good stir", not only the presidency, but also the financial crisis, which is being dealt with now.
The EU's seven-year budget must also be approved, because of the current economic situation, which is much more complicated.
If the budget is simpler and more effective, which sectors will be given priority, which countries will receive more support and which will receive less?
The Ambassador also recalled her main motto, with which she arrived in Europe: "About Europe with clarity".
"I don't like ugly abbreviations, foreign words, or slang that people don't understand".
'How can a citizen understand that Brussels is not really inventing cucumbers, curved or round cucumbers, bananas of various sizes or that nobody is going to ban Olomouc cheese?'
It also aims to make more use of the EU environment and bring more Czech citizens closer to the European institutions.
Europe of speeds awaits us
According to the ambassador, the Czechs are known for being Eurosceptic and people perceive the negative aspects more than the positive.
He also deplored the low participation of Czechs in the European institutions.
The blame lies with a multitude of factors, such as the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivational messages, but also the lack of support from the Czechs.
In addition to the success of the Czech presidency, he highlighted the strength and collaboration of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when a Pole and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak approaches me, a Frenchman next to me says, 'What, you're all done, you Visegrad group?' and he's not amused at all".
In the future, according to Vicenová, the EU will face tough new rules on budgetary policy for the Member States.
The concept of the two speed limits is perceived as very real, if not more so, in Europe than the new concept of the European Federation.
"We have countries in the Eurozone and countries outside the Eurozone".
'We have the Schengen area and we have the enhanced cooperation procedure.'
"It was said for the first time that only countries that want to cooperate and those that don't, stay out".
"These procedures will be increasing and will strengthen the two-speed Europe", hopes Vicenová.
He also stressed the role of the Czech Republic and Herman van Rompuy in implementing the principle that all issues affecting the EU as a whole should be discussed between the Member States, not just the members of the Eurozone.
Brand story:
The innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If one were to look for a term that would very accurately define IBM's strategy, the most approximate would be "long term".
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet has passed a hundred years since its founding.
The foundation for this long-term nature was laid by the firm's first head, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the slogan that many of the world's problems can be solved if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his trademark, around which he would build the life of the future giant (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis for a carefully constructed corporate culture.
"For us, IBM means thinking long term, moving continuously towards the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it stayed true to its basic principles, but without fear of changes around it.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We hope to prosper even more in our second century", said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current director, during his anniversary.
A sophisticated system
Watson, already in the 1930s, was concerned with the care of his employees as Baťa's businessman in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American operators to enjoy paid holidays, insurance, elegant uniforms and a sophisticated compensation system that rewarded the best inventors and salesmen.
The same sophistication is maintained by IBM in the long-term relationship with the customer.
