How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state travel agencies in the then Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time mostly sold travel only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, afterwards the Yugoslav regime leaned west and the travel of Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even within the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies in those days also offered trips to the West, but one had to line up with a sleeping bag and spend the night like that, or have "good acquaintances" at the agency.
Still not all was won.
The so-called "promise of exchange" that was the condition for travel to the West was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs would acquire.
The way of travelling in the Czech Republic has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, that the current favourite destination, Croatia, was not free to travel to until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s, visa-free travel to neighbouring Western European countries was introduced, leading to a huge wave of short-term visits, particularly to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, were not tired of excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in tents in parks, since our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take food (cans, sausages, etc.) with them to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech krone, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was rising and with it the average wage, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand, from 1997 onwards, the agencies began to prepare travel regularly using charter connections, which made travel prices fall incredibly compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts on the volume of passengers.
By the late 1990s, Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the United States, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened back in 2000, when the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, thanks to a huge demand, and went to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries have been taking off every year, and this winter, direct flights from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations will be made.
The exotic countries are now visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States abolished visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in their history, spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than 15 thousand Czech crowns per capita on travel abroad, including the costs of the place of stay.
An ordinary general assembly to elect the president, which could end in a stalemate again.
For almost five months now, Czech football has been without a president and it is likely that Ivan Hašek's successor as President of the Czech Football Federation (FAČR) will not be known even after the next Extraordinary General Assembly, which will take place this Thursday in Nymburk.
In fact, no agreement has yet been reached on the voting rules to be followed.
Without them, you cannot even vote to choose between the three candidates.
The Czech football presidents are Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
Hašek resigned in June, not without summoning his colleagues to find a strong person who could handle football in the future.
However, after the Hašek era ended, a controversy broke out between the two federations of the association unable to reach an agreement to choose a common candidate.
This was evident on September 16 when the new president had to be elected.
The delegates of the General Assembly met in vain at the National House (Národní dům), located in the Prague district of Smíchov, because the talks had been blocked and not only as to the method of election.
No consensus was reached as to who in the General Assembly had the right to vote - only the legal representatives or also the full-powered delegates.
From that moment on, and because of this single point, a partial agreement was reached, supported also by the recommendation of the Institute of State and Law, according to which full representation is not possible.
However, disputes over the electoral code remain open.
The Commission has not been able to shed any more light on the situation, even the Executive Committee, which at its ordinary or extraordinary meetings has basically not resolved anything.
The opinion on the possibility of voting has changed a couple of times already, but the nerve point is still the same.
The question is: how do we proceed in the third round to avoid a deadlock?
"The dispute is about whether to proceed according to the statutes or find another model", says Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-presidents of the FAČR, which represents professional football from the association's management.
According to the model proposed in the statutes, in the third round, the candidate who has the highest percentage of support in the federation to which he will present his candidacy will win.
The Moravian Region is willing to reach a compromise so that it can win that candidate with a higher total percentage of votes in both federations.
The Bohemian side, however, imposes the condition that the winner, according to these percentage calculations, must have a majority of at least two thirds.
"This would, however, make no sense of the previous two rounds and would completely negate the concept of a bicameral system", Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, according to which it would be best not to touch the order and vote according to the applicable statutes.
This is something which Tomaš Paclík surprisingly agrees with, although it is assumed that the electoral rules laid down by the statutes of all candidates are more suited to Pelta.
"I would like to see the vote as strictly as possible in accordance with the statutes".
"So that no nonsense is made about the representatives like in the last General Assembly", says the owner of Victoria Plzen, who is running for the first time and who directs his remarks mainly against Pelta.
Pelta is still optimistic.
He said that the new president would be decided in Nymburk and he believed that the candidates would cooperate constructively in the future.
"All the passions will be appeased by today's match of our national team in the European Championship.
"Football will be the main player again, and so cooperation will be more generous", says the representative of Jablonice, which has more experience in football management, both at professional and regional level.
Rajchl is the most reticent.
"I hope that an agreement will be reached, but unfortunately the situation is much more complicated".
"It's not the Bohemian-Moravian conflict, but there are attempts to adjust the rules to their own convenience".
"This may result in a new blockade of the General Assembly".
"Anyway, I hope common sense will prevail", Rajchl said.
There is not much time left for all parties to reach an agreement.
Some negotiations had to be held in Montenegro, but who can know until the match starts whether the football team will be complete?
The special plane, in which they had to travel to Podgorica, among others the vice-presidents Dalibor Kucera and Rajchl, has not left this morning for technical problems in Prague, having to look for an alternative to transport part of the executive committee to the place where the qualification match will take place.
Perhaps the decisive meeting, finally, could be the one that will take place at ministerial level, which, they say, will be held this Wednesday.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Sports, would very much like to bring the divided parties into the most powerful sports organization in the country so that an agreement can be reached.
