Krischanitz was the best choice for it.
Not only because he sensitively reformed Joseph Olbrichs's Vienna secession, expanded it and was awarded the competition, but also because he studied with Schwanzwer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him an "important and immense place", where he contemplated "almost every weekend" exhibitions.
He knew the project and the problem of the building, which disappeared with his move to Vienna in its change of use with generosity and ease.
In the current reforms there are big problems, the building was "an energy devourer", Krischanitz said.
The windows of the glass facade were changed, a glass fiber reinforced insulating glass was installed and the glass ceiling was replaced by a special safety glass.
Thermal bridges and steel beams were reinforced or replaced and asbestos roofs were rehabilitated.
Two basements were used for the new use, a downed light panel between the house and the street provides lighting, a bridge serves to enter the almost new building, but still the Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors remain, the house is painted in old mahogany tones and protected against oxidation.
