Walls have eyes: How researchers are studying you on Facebook
Before he became the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy who aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to carrying out a July massacre in Norway that left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time before his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
"We found it wasn't that hard to reach them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British think tank DEMOS.
Facebook's personal information storage is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy - the way marketers have been using for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes toward violence, and optimism about their own future.
By reaching out through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research", says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind a computer screen".
DEMOS' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health issues to social trends as expressed in likes, wall posts and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is driving a research boom, boosting the number of academic papers with the site's name in the title to nearly 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't get close to with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you tried to poll people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them".
"You'd have to go through the party, and they'd never let you in", Bartlett says.
"Facebook deletes all that - you go straight to them".
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address social health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that college students who talked about their drinking feats on Facebook were at significantly higher risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent about the subject.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who posts too many status updates with his or her booze.
"You can't treat a problem if you can't diagnose it", said Dimitri Christakis, the co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Institute for Child Research, the Washington Post reported.
"We've found a way to identify at-risk children who would otherwise not be diagnosed".
Facebook is also constantly "pinning" its own population for data.
The site's Data Team has compiled statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expected voter turnout in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using information that can be accessed - longtime digital freedom advocates argue that the site should make its vast amount of data available to others for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not - the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is allowing the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don't even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
"I don't think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be looking at their profiles", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study he conducted with the public Facebook walls of students.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends".
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that a research subject is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it's impossible to know which part of a user's profile information and wall posts are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off of Facebook are two completely different things", says Selwyn.
That's why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a paper clip and a pen are still the best research tools that no one can use.
"There's no substitute for going into the real world and talking to real people", he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about the social -- and a lot of the social still happens offline".
