7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Missed Interview, Shown at a Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, there were those who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the technological genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted off as a preview of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was no doubt a self-proclaimed designer, dreamer, and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a flow diagram yonki - a man who believed that many executives suffered from "a disease of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there's a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for over an hour with Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
By this time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensely on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly re-edited archive footage is the basis for the 68-minute Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which arrives in Landmark theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there's great silence between the questions and the answers -- 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs's perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing him to move faster toward the issues or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there's something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, where Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It's one thing to read posthumous reviews of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after I explained everything in detail here, he went and did it.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I've always asked, "Why do you do things?" and the answers they give you invariably are, "Oh, that's just the way it's done".
Nobody knows why they do what they do, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs details his efforts to simplify Apple's accounting.
Disconcerted by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made on the fly, and then adjusted with a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that ensured they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
About the Pope joke:
Jobs tells of the "Blue Box" that he built himself with Steve Wozniak -- a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make free long-distance calls.
Much has been written about the device, but Jobs' euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world half a dozen times and you'd yell through the pay phone and come back a minute later to the next door pay phone", Jobs says with a laugh.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world".
The two of us, we didn't know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing -- it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious prank that he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the Pope himself was awakened to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my view of what a company was and how well they treated their employees".
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was the size of a suitcase, had a little cathode-tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I'd get a trip to HP as a teenager and I'd waste my time with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Early in his career, as he was selling a handful of motherboards, a client asked him if he could assemble the whole equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and went outside and found a designer.
90 days later, we had a mouse that we could build for 15 dollars and that was totally reliable.
On the big companies losing strength:
Long before he led the Apple renaissance, Jobs prophetically predicted the way many industry leaders would stumble on his vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers and printers, and what?"
You have a monopoly on market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it's these kinds of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are kicked out of the decision-making forum.
The product genius that led to that monopoly position is rotten because of people who don't have the notion of good products vs. bad products - the knowledge of the necessary craft.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
They took defeat from victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There's a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows".
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make -- some things you can't make electrons do, glass does them, robots do them, factories do them.
You have to keep 5,000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
It all comes down to taste in the end - it comes down to trying to expose yourself to the best that a team of humans has ever done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed about stealing great ideas.
Part of what made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer science, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas dine with health care law rivals as the court accepts the case.
On the day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to consider the politically controversial question of whether to accept the challenge to President Obama's health care law, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were hosted at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will present the case before the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to study the review petitions thoroughly.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the comprehensive health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying cry for conservative activists across the country.
The magistrates agreed to admit the lawsuit and, in fact, a historic 5 1/2 hour plea is expected in March, and the result will likely further cloud the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court's decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear in court and argue that the law should be thrown out will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. attorney general during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has long been dedicated to defending conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that defied the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel hours after the court's preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees was, among others, Mitch McConnell, the most prominent Republican in the Senate and an outspoken opponent of the health care law.
Special guests at dinner?
It's nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it's not something that conflicts with ethical standards.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct that governs the actions of lower federal judges.
If they were not, they might be said to fall under Canon Code 4C, which says: "A judge may attend events to raise funds for law-related organizations and others, although the judge may not be a speaker, an honored guest, or appear on the program of such an event".
However, the absolute proximity of Scalia and Thomas to two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
"This impressive ethical gap and indifference to the code goes against the demands of several justices that the court abide by the same rules that apply to all federal judges", said Bob Edgar, the president of Common Cause.
"The judges were rewarded at a fundraiser with lawyers who have pending cases before the court".
Your appearance and assistance in fundraising for this event undermines any claim of impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in criticism that they say too easily mixes the court's activity with the agenda pushed by groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it's magistrate Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan served as attorney general in the Obama administration when the first legal challenges to the law were filed in the court of first instance.
Her critics have pressed Kagan to abstain from the case, saying she was too involved in defending the law to be impartial now.
Kagan has given no indication that he's going to.
