How to detect a lie
A glance at the latest headlines shows us how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment allegations with several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone asserting to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself with his denials quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And again, no one who lived through it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating on school and college exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given test answers to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's right, a lot of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Liar detection, or "lying localization", is an essential skill that we all need to acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, Charade, where the goal is to exclaim, "I've got you", cheat detection is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the last six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars do look in the eyes.
They don't always stutter, babble, blush or get restless.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can get to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question forming, and timing.
I spent several years probing the scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, make them feel comfortable, manage their own emotions, and intuitively feel how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-directed lies", while women tell more "other-directed lies" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less frequently to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they usually tell tend to be "huge".
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline".
It helps provide benchmarks for measuring changes later.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristics.
You better know if someone normally kicks their foot all the time so you don't make unfair accusations when you see their feet kicking in the middle of a meeting.
Next, look for groups of deceptive behaviors, verbal and nonverbal.
Consider these groups of behaviors as warning signs, not evidence of deception.
Cheaters may freeze their upper body trying to remember their story, they may point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit "post-interview exhaust" - that exaggerated sigh of relief and post-interview change once all the difficult questions are over.
Often the interrogators make it appear falsely that the interview has ended just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson went all the way down and used the time spent while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat may also use language that distances them: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question in its entirety.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I know... to my understanding".
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to detect deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
