Climate adversity slowed the economy
During the first year of the administration of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa, unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has decreased and the economy has contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, self-named the change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, no growth is observed, instead a deterioration is recorded in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures in February, in addition to causing millions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the state economy's chances of growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of affected by frosts, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, damage was caused in 582 thousand 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent had partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a constant increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloenses were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Economically Active Population, for the second quarter the rate became 5.28 percent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 percent, a rate that in number throws more than 74 thousand people without it unemployed, an increase in respect of the first semester of 18 thousand 969 individuals.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out from public policy.
"What is being seen is a growth of unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to the effects of a restriction of resources by the legislation that was approved in the congress to combat money laundering, and for people who grab dollars illicitly it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something", he said.
Migration stopped
Lopez Cervantes pointed out that the increase in unemployment also has a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state in search of work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first by the difficulties to enter, and second because entering already have also many difficulties to find work, those people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which makes the unemployment rises", he said.
Informal
The analysis of the Sinaloese labour market is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among the working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being quoted as a worker before any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the state's labor backlogs are low salaries, the entity has the lowest remunerations in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Provision.
The average monthly income of Sinalo workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
In addition to the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 the largest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment of the last 10 years is recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June of the state IED amounted to 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a fall of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded during the same period of the previous year.
The State Government's Economic Development Secretariat, on the other hand, accounts for a total investment of 17 billion 280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt
In view of the economic contraction scenario, the state government requested in July to the state congress the approval of a credit for 3 billion pesos, which would be destined to investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to reactivate the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2 thousand 600 million pesos, and until November have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensely to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, we have to align the effort of everyone and especially the good march of this new team of Government, we hope that next year will be much better", he said.
Economic slowdown
Loredo López said that events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn around fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing much below the expectations we had", he said.
Redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, it is necessary to lead the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that it has been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated", he said.
Work to be done
The President of the Coparmex highlighted the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms I would say that the Government has been striving to give good results in different matters, in terms of economic development there are some advances but it is important that a long-term program is developed", he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its way of conducting public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think that the Government is aware that there is work to be done", he said.
