The 2015 "analogue blackout" in Mexico is now being validated
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies brought against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogue shutdown" from 2021 to 2015, when the eight votes necessary to invalidate it were not met.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when issuing the decree detailing the actions to be followed to concretise the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With that result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was dismissed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this remains in force.
The draft judgment, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a faculty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to impugn the decree, and upon admitting the demands, minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions in it set for the digital transition.
The plenary resolution also rejected the demand by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also in charge of the minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the minister-president said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to prepare.
"I also do not think that if I did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector correspond to the federal executive, who has a constitutional mandate, the rectorate of the State.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years, resulting in better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
He said that delaying the change would be postponing the benefits of digitalisation, which implies a decision of public interest, which does not have a solely technical dimension, "as it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic rectorate of the State, encompasses a group of attributions that the Constitution leads to the faculty of the state Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and have done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, when issuing the impugned decree, that in some way invades the sphere of competence of the Congress, because it is providing in the administrative sphere the observance of the laws issued by the Legislature, he said.
They analyze the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data thrown by the PREP, the difference between first and second place in the election of governor is just 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total acts.
The possibility of "vote by vote" counting is a reality in the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to data released by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is just 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total acts.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just last November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local rules with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not homologate its Political Constitution nor its Electoral Code of the State or its Electoral Justice Law, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before concluding the legal term so that they could enter into force in the present electoral process and the governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication in the timeframes provided in the Law of the Official Periodic of the State, with the argument that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and qualified as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state president to constitutional reforms, since he has no right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of "vote by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes for one or more electoral parcels may take place in the event that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; the record of the vote and counting does not exist in the file of the box or is not in the possession of the president of the box; or, when there are obvious errors or alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total number of votes cast in all the voting boxes may be counted where there is evidence that the difference between the presumed winner of the election in question and the candidate who came second in the voting is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express request from the representative of the party and/or coalition which nominated the second of the nominated candidates.
The total count of the vote may also be carried out if, at the end of the ordinary counting, it is established that the difference between the candidate presumed to have won and the candidate placed second is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate came second, in which case the electoral packages which have been the subject of partial counting shall be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is just 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total acts.
