The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The prime minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put that country on the brink of economic disaster.
The Italian prime minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian president on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present the president with the result of his talks with the political parties in their attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase", the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say that he will be able to form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "framework is now well delineated", he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, while Italy is battling a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore the shattered confidence in Italy.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to act quickly, the instability of the markets put the yield on Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7%, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be bailed out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employers' group Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government".
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency.
Monti's chances of success were boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which was forced to resign on Saturday by the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result", Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told the press.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could trigger a devastating new attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organisations.
He'll end his round of meetings Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Bailing out Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone's current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before the elections are called.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist it should be made up of only technicians, an indication of his reservations about a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources noted that mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
