For their Costa Rican fans, it's a dream come true that Pearl Jam is going to play in Costa Rica, are they aware of what their fans are going through?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once and on vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we'll be able to stay there for a few days.
So we're excited to bring our music there.
I ask because there's a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the days before.
What do they tell their most ardent followers?
Thank you for staying by our side through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even refer to his concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played over the last 21 years have happened over the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of huge shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully that got us in shape for this gig in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle, and for both of those things, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; that's how we found out, through people who love surfing.
Watching the tour, they've been delivering huge shows with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never touched there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We're going to try to give the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we're going to try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You guys never rehearse the repertoire.
What's this about?
I think it's partly because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to pick which songs to play each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't played in a while, it keeps us focused and it also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we might have forgotten.
