How do you find a balance?
As we've grown, it's been easier to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too much because it's easy to fall into that game of the big crowds and the people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for music, that reminds you that you should respect music and what it brought, not get carried away by being famous and being a rock star, something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some really good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for almost three years and never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we're still very close friends with Bruce [Fairweather] and Greg [Gilmore], who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture I think about the amazing person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and so much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be the opening act for the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yeah, the production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we're excited to see what Las Robertas can offer live and it should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics to Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that comes to his mind.
As a bass player, what are your influences?
There's so many of them.
Among the first ones that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant even though it's no longer a fad?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the other bands that came out at the same time, and, if there's any relevance now, I think it's a wonderful thing because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that maybe seem lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs even though they may sound a little bit positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them to me, I cried when I heard them and they're deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there's some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that's dark.
Peru:
Fujimori is hospitalized again for medical examinations
Former president Alberto Fujimori was admitted Tuesday to a public hospital to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength he has in his legs, his primary care physician said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his rule (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including a cancer of the tongue for which he has undergone four operations and is kept under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Channel N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated on four times for cancer of the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which have been added other pathologies such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, renal calculi, arterial hypertension and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor enumerated.
Fujimori has been in detention since September 2007 at the National Directorate of Special Operations of the police.
In April 2009 he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the killing of 25 people by an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his rule.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and composed of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the high point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the collectivity of Uruguayans residing in Mexico, according to the agenda disseminated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "propitious for the exchange of information on all political matters between the two nations", as published by the Presidency of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderon to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when the French president, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country in a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked Uruguay's rejection and the call for consultation of its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been presiding over the G20 since November, a group made up of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries, and has had an agreement with the South American country since January this year to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the conclusion of tax exchange agreements in order to get out of the "gray list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which is made up of countries that have not implemented all international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
In the trade area, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The moustached plumber is going 3D with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before has he done so in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which arrives this month in stores around the world, has been designed from the start to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS handheld console, which allows you to play in three dimensions without the need to use glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to tell how the stereoscopy without glasses should work", said the head of Nintendo's specialized press in Spain, Omar Álvarez, during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Alvarez indicated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game originally designed for that support", as until now hits like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo's spokesman has maintained that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Álvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to hook less skilled users.
Once overcome, the most experienced players will be able to take a "second turn" at the levels of the game, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This incursion of Super Mario into the three dimensions also means the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that has not occurred since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo winked at the fans of the saga and repeated the formula of the success of previous installments, consisting of the plumber of the mustache will have to travel platforms mined of dangers with the aim of freeing Princess Peach.
Although the player will find novelties in the moves, environments, costumes and enemies and also a "playable" Luigi.
Colom endorses the extradition of Portillo to the United States
President Álvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he has processed the extradition of ex-governor Alfonso Portillo to answer in the United States for the conspiracy for the laundering of US$70 million.
This is the end of the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the northern country that claimed Portillo to be tried there.
At a press conference, Colom said his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and executive, given that a sentencing court had already ordered the extradition.
He said that during his term of office he "did not get his hands" into judicial resolutions and handled all the extraditions he has known.
In addition to Portillo, they will be extradited Sergio Ruano Marroquín, for murder and serious injuries, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Colom did is an executive procedure after all the judicial and constitutional instances to prosecute the former president of 2000-2004 were exhausted.
According to the resolutions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo must be extradited once he has solved his legal situation in Guatemala and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted for the defamation of Q120 million in the Ministry of Defense when he was president, which was the process that preceded the extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed and reactivated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people at risk
The institution was born to prevent the fall in the marginality of untrained kids
The first 25 years of the Trinijove social support institution are important: 6,000 young people at risk of exclusion have received help to overcome a difficult situation over the course of this quarter of a century.
In addition to this, there are now over 100 jobs for this social group.
The anniversary was marked yesterday at an event held in the former Fabra i Coats factory complex, attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was born in the Trinitat Vella neighbourhood in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with little training, unemployment, with problems of radicalisation or in a situation of marginalization.
The celebration in Sant Andreu yesterday brought together a large number of leaders from institutions and entities that have been working with the association for 25 years.
The varied political representation, in full electoral time, showed the unitary character of Trinijove's work.
Along with the President of the Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the event was attended by the former socialist Education Councillor, Ernest Maragall, and the former mayor and current ecosocialist councillor Ricard Gomà.
The current councillor of Benestar Social i Família, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the general director of the social work of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa, also attended the great hall of the Fabra i Coats.
He said that Trinijove was born in a very difficult time and that the current one is also difficult, but added that the work done so far "is a good basis".
The President set Trinijove as an example for knowing how to fight against bad circumstances and for giving hope to people in difficulty.
"The crisis is not something new for the entity and for the work it does", he said.
A farmhouse where macrofiestas were held has been evacuated
The invaders had taken 11 of the 13 floors of the building, in Balmes, 51
The 12 occupants left the estate yesterday at noon without offering resistance.
Everything seems to indicate that the nightmare that lived the residents of 51 Balmes Street has come to an end.
Twelve people left the building voluntarily yesterday at noon, where they were organizing unlawful macrofiestas that despaired the neighborhood, by judicial order and without the need for police intervention.
When the operation was over, the door lock was changed to prevent a repeat of the situation.
"From now on there will be access control", the administrator said.
The occupants, who had invaded 11 of the 13 floors of the building - the rest are inhabited - took away all the electrical installation and part of the water, in addition to painting the walls and leaving waste of all kinds, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
The first three floors were the scene of mass parties, which lasted up to two days and despaired the tenants.
Next to the building is a nightclub, Balmes 51, which has also been damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that since the building was occupied the business has fallen by 80%.
The owner of the disco points out that the invaders of the estate made it unfair competition, since they sold the cups at three euros, while in the disco they are 10.
The owner of the leisure venue had to respond to neighbourly complaints about noise, while, as she pointed out, the inconveniences are not caused by the customers of the disco, but by the inhabitants of the occupied house and, above all, the attendees to the parties that were organized there, which had increased their frequency and intensity in recent weeks, according to the angry neighbors of the area.
The manager of the disco explained that the inconveniences were so great that she even reached an agreement with the owner of the property and nine months ago "forgives" the rent.
The Urban Guard also confirmed that over the past few weeks it had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation.
The president of the PP municipal group in the city, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had claimed last week "to immediately evict the building to end the problems of coexistence and civism that produce the neighbors, as well as the degradation of the area".
The popular leader explained that before the summer there was only one floor of the building occupied, but over the past months the occupiers had been entering all floors of the building and in almost all floors, and that in some even have been robberies.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to end impunity and be forceful against the incivility that has been generated in the farm".
Also yesterday, the Mossos evacuated a building in Nou Barris.
At 15.30 hours the police went to 35 rue de Mont-ral, after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed four people accessing the building.
All four were arrested at the time.
Park or mountain?
The architects agree on the occasion of the call beyond polemics over fees
The municipal contest on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-80s, at the height of the now-defunct Barcelona Metropolitan Corporation (CMB), the administration printed a few promotional stamps for Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
In fact, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York's Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park was again situated, in the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented in the north-south axis but up (mountain) -down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a nature park is consistent with this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with the boars in the role of Yogi Bear.
It was in these until, in September, the city council called a mega-competition consisting of 16 contests for as many access doors to Collserola.
A door is a reference to the idea of a park, no doubt.
Either that or someone's trying to put doors on the field.
The question is, Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its merely organizational aspect and for what it implies of reflection on the city is the topic of conversation among all Barcelona architects.
It is almost a recurring theme to be touched when two members of this ancient caste of chosen ones recognize each other in an elevator.
This fact gives rise to one of the few coincidences between the opinions of three Barcelona architects and university professors who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Mòdol and Marta Bayona: the contest is timely.
For Roldán, after addressing the coastal front, "it becomes necessary" to debate "the mountain front", since Ildefons Cerdà's speech, the one about the green apples, has not been carried out.
"It is worth starting from the premise that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, it is very accessible.
Collserola is more complex", says the architect for whom the title "Collserola doors" contains a "lexical trap": one must not think of them "as access to a park, but the delimitation of areas where one has to act".
Mòdol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, calls the proposal an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
The dangers derived from the "uncertainty of today's public space" after the experience of the 80's in the Fòrum area "the swan's song".
The first fear is the very delimitation of boundaries on where it can be built.
"To limit something is to fix the next step", that is, to overcome it.
"We need to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [in reference to the Metropolitan General Plan (PGM) ] can lead to real disasters".
More closely related to the question, Mòdol believes that, to simplify, the Vallés side of Collserola "can be understood as a park, not Barcelona", for a merely topographical question.
Mòdol recalls that there is already a work done by the Patronat of Collserola that "should not fall into disrepair", although he is grateful for the opportunity that the city council offers to its guild to intervene in this project "from the very beginning".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe conduit that allows architects to enter the debate, but "doubts" about whether this technical profile should lead the multidisciplinary teams ("all a hit", he points out) that have had to be created: "Architects should be just a tool".
Bayona insinuates that the answer to the question that gives the title to this piece is complex, because in the bases of the contest there is a lack of a global vision of Collserola: "16 cross-sectional contests have been called - he says - in the mountain-sea sense, but there is no longitudinal reading, which sees and understands the area as a whole".
This causes you, at least in your case, to have chosen to participate in all 16 competitions.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors may clash in program and definition with that of the architect of the next door.
In his view, yes, the city should ensure that the strip immediately above the Dalt Ronde should provide, throughout its length, for a equipment area which would make a smooth transition between the city and the green.
Casino forgives Jonas Larrazábal and he will be released
After 72 days of taking root, the legal representative of Casino Red granted the pardon to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey from the process that was followed for alleged blackmail
After 72 days in prison, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal will be released after the legal representative of Casino Red granted him a pardon before the Second District Criminal Court, which is pursuing a process for blackmail against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on the Casino Royale, the owner of the Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, made public a series of photographs and videos in which Manuel Jonás allegedly demanded the payment of an economic fee so that the regiomontano council would allow the clandestine operation of the betting house.
After the public denunciation, the State Prosecutor's Office opened a criminal process against the brother of the Panista mayor and on September 2 he was arrested and imprisoned for 30 days.
After four hours before the Public Ministry's Agent 3 in Patrimonial Deeds, he was transferred to the Arraigo 1 House, located in the Old Quarter of the state capital.
He remained there for the next 49 days when a second arrest warrant was issued after the public prosecutor's office dismissed the co-defendants and organized crime.
On 19 October he was transferred to the Cadereyta penitentiary for allegedly blackmailing the owners of Casino Red with one and a half million pesos; however, he only remained a few hours in the medium security prison as there were death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to continue the trial interned in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, he was ordered to be apprehended by the secretary of the Second District Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that almost two months of investigations had proved enough evidence to determine the guilt of Jonás, such as the payment of 1.5 million pesos to the representatives of the betting house in exchange for allowing the operation of the same.
This Monday, the legal representative of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, went to judge José Luis Pecina to ask for forgiveness for the brother of the mayor regio; so in the next few hours he could recover his freedom.
During the legal diligence, the agent of the Public Ministry assigned to the Court, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez if the damage had been repaired and which of the partners of the betting house was the one who granted the pardon, although the lawyer tried to reserve the name.
Based on case 197/2011, Jonás Larrazábal was granted a legal pardon and no further claims can be made about the process followed; in addition, no compensation for damage or punishment will be demanded.
After the hearing of the legal representative of the bookmaker, at about 15:50 the immediate release of Larrazabal Breton was ordered.
The secretary of the Court, Jorge Yánez, moved to the jail of the municipality of San Nicolás de los Garza to notify Jonás that he has been legally pardoned and his file will be archived.
You will also notify him of the immediate release order issued by the judge.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which the secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter was directly impacted on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"Elements that appear to indicate the unit had multiple ground contact, the blades made contact with trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage".
He also said the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the requirements to transport personnel.
He also said that in the investigations made in the impact area, no pieces were reported on the ground.
"In a search report no parts or components of the ship were found elsewhere, the impact was presented in a structural manner.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers, and had adequate requirements for transporting passengers.
The terrain has a seven-degree slope at the 30-degree incline.
At the moment, the secretary said it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, the investigation may take several months, even a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, director general of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the Presidential Staff helicopter was operating at cruise speed and that this happened on a soft upward terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact", he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations the flight was performed under visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM located suitable conditions at take-off, as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, layers of low-altitude cloudiness were present.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloudiness conditions the crew sought a lower elevation and higher visibility area towards the valley of Cuernavaca.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the aircraft's last radar record match, probably before impact there was no loss of control or alteration in flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred in a straight and lateral trajectory.
The dispersion pattern of the aircraft debris suggests that the helicopter was impacted on the ground in conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion detected:
At the scene of the accident, there is still no evidence of any explosion or fire in the wreckage.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During fieldwork, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,000 feet above mean sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably disarticulated along the route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search in a wider area than the agreed site, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found around the crash, which strengthens the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
Social Security conducts research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people; it is supported by specialists from the IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting a study to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity' protocol, which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center Century XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population, whether or not entitled to participate, to attend the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Mexico West State) and that since October 8, the activity is being carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Mexico East State).
Once the target of 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, the World Diabetes Day, the aim is to bring together three thousand children and young people aged between six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on food.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of disease, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He said that on Saturdays, all participants are subjected to anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetic tests (seeking to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz Lopez pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in weight in minors.
'The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was a 77 percent increase in obesity among boys and 47 percent among girls; there was also a dramatic increase in overweight,' said the IMSS specialist.
He said the justification for the search for the markers was that the country's population differs from others because of its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows detecting if they are overweight or obese.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) on the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is kept confidential, and doctors give it in writing to parents, who are told about each measurement and lifestyle change they must make to prevent illness.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic ailments: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the television and using transportation instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, i.e. the increased consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamas, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
Asphalt from UNAM would prevent potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of the UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental conditions and temperature
If the signals sent by the paving were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand bumps each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt paving is adequate, the bumps could be reduced in quantity or even eliminated completely.
In his lecture A technological opinion of the bumps, delivered in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory in charge of him develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltens, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it is almost solid, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is changing during the day according to the environmental conditions and temperature, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt layer, which is made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
By passing vehicles and generating forces, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, the chemical engineer thought, they would spread even better.
On top of the asphalt carpet, abundant, is a last layer called the rolling carpet, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt sheet and provide friction on the road.
As it is the part of the pavement that will receive and diffuse the stresses, the rolling stock also needs to be of the right thickness and care must be taken with the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it considerably affects the performance of the asphalt pavement.
When the soil becomes wet, water diffuses inside the carpet and is difficult to get out, this causes softening of all layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a bump, he said, the first to wear out is the bearing film and only then is the asphalt folder affected, but the damage does not occur instantaneously, but is a process that should be attended to at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Investigators explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement should always be in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is met, to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already even on the market and allow to repair the bumps with ease and without need to use high temperatures.
