That was the work of the tracer who identified the body of Alfonso Cano.
A California loboscopist went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4th, a CTI lofoscopist from Cali made history as the man who confirmed the identity of the FARC's top leader, "Alfonso Cano", through the collection of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lofoscopists working in the CTI section, that week it was Eliazar González's turn to be available, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the judicial investigation area for 21 years.
At the start of his career, González worked in Chocó municipalities, where he often had to intern for more than five days in the jungle to reach the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after completing the corresponding courses, he specialized in lofoscopy, which is the study of the skin of friction, that is, of the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to wear minimal clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to carry the decadactyl card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the site of the body, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, which was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local farmer, no glasses, and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplant, and a flashlight, Elias compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those on the card.
His eye didn't fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the top leader of the Farc.
In search of the trail
For a dactyloscopist from Sijín de Cali, the recognition made by president Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know what we do.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin for error, that can become key in solving crimes.
Apart from identifying corpses, lofoscopists support investigations for crimes such as robbery and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When caught, many criminals present false IDs or do not have papers.
We'll take their fingerprints and run them through the database.
The investigator related that in one case of theft, he had to remove a piece of a house wall, for in that place the thief had leaned his hand to take out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts", he recalled.
Fingerprints can also rule out or reassert suspects in homicide cases.
They just found a dead man, with liquor bottles around him.
Through investigation it was determined that a relative could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a print on the bottle matched.
Although this doesn't guarantee that it was the killer, it does place him at the scene of the crime.
A CTI fingerprint technician explained that on objects "the fingerprints are removed with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a graft or tape is used to lift them.
After that, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or the Registrar's Office.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians", the CTI expert said.
He clarified that not everything is as shown in the CSI television show.
Just as not everything that glitters is gold, not everything you touch becomes a print.
However, if it can be used, if the respective matching is made.
"Indignant" people defy authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters were crowding in front of Zuccotti Square to camp.
A large part of them complied with the eviction order and moved to a nearby paruk.
The members of the Occupy Wall Street movement challenged New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to re-enter, under the auspices of a court order, the Manhattan square from which they were evicted early in the morning and by trying to occupy another park in the Big Apple.
Hundreds of protesters were crowding in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to access thanks to a court order allowing the "indignados" to camp again on the spot, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction by occupying a park further north of the city, where there have been new arrests.
"Our idea is that, if the court does not allow us to camp in the square again, we will settle somewhere else and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations", said one of the spokesmen of the Occupy Wall Street movement, Mark Bray.
Bray said the "indignados"' response to the eviction of their camp dictated personally by New York mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting forced evacuation of the site and allowing protesters to camp.
In addition, the "indignados" proceeded to occupy a new park located at the confluence of downtown Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which connects New York and New Jersey, and is owned by the parish of Trinity Church.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but then the Police went and proceeded to arrest some of the protesters, although Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, while he assured Efe that he saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization says several hundred people had settled at the point, where a delegation of religious leaders has already moved in support of the movement and tried to mediate with the police.
Meanwhile, the Zuccotti square - which is a private property - remains closed pending a court hearing scheduled for Tuesday to analyze the legality of the early morning evacuation.
Some of the protesters displaced there were carrying and distributing copies of that judicial order at these hours and even handing them over to the agents guarding the square, which caused "some small clashes", said Bray, who denounced that some officers struck the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evicting Ocupa Wall Street members or applying "laws that were issued after the occupation began or prohibiting protesters from re-entering the park with stores or other property they used previously".
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, because of that court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and the protesters, who he warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to re-install with tents and sleeping bags.
The mayor personally defended the early morning eviction of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which around 200 arrests were made and which was decided because the protesters were "violating the law".
Bloomberg explained that he ordered the evacuation of the square because it was becoming "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, to hurt other people", as "some businesses had received threats" and the neighbors feared "for their quality of life".
"The eviction this morning was disgusting and shows that at the bottom Bloomberg is more interested in preserving the financial interests than those of American workers", added the movement's spokesman, who accused the mayor of "lacking respect for freedom of expression".
The "Occupy Wall Street" leaders also indicated that they plan to organize "big actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions, to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on September 17.
