Japan Revives After the Earthquake
GDP grows 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that turned into a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe the country has suffered since World War II.
Initial estimates by the Tokyo government put the material losses at $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have subsided.
After three consecutive quarters of fall, the data on gross domestic product between July and September definitely turned the page: GDP increased by 1.5% compared with the previous quarter and by 6% at an annualized rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - is also the fastest growth since January-March 2010.
The recovery is partly explained by the upturn in the purchase of machinery to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
Indeed, firms increased their investments by 1,1%, compared to the decrease of 0,9% in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increases.
The real revulsion of the Japanese economy, however, is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse to take advantage of crises to strengthen - or rebuild - infrastructure, to use shortcomings to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which now accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable climbed by 1%, driven by the increase in spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has entrusted itself to the internal market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "refuge values" chosen by investors fleeing the euro zone debt crisis and the gloomy forecasts of the US, a privilege that weighs like a slab on the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of the big tech groups.
Toyota and Sony, for example, attributed their weak results between July and September to the yen's price.
As long as the markets continue their siege of the EU's peripheral countries, the government of Yoshihiko Noda does not let down its guard.
"We must be alert to the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen", said Economic Policy Secretary Motohisa Furukawa yesterday.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The OECD said that most member countries showed more clear signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates turning points in the world economy highlighted that the major powers are slowing down.
It fell four tenths to 100.4 points, down from 100.8 in August.
The euro area even fell below the average of 100, falling eight tenths to 99.13 points.
Athens again feeds doubts
Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the Conservatives won't sign any written commitments.
With peripheral risk premiums soaring and uncertainty re-established in the parks, Greece continues to be entangled in the maze leading to the exit from the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the 'consensus' of the new Greek transitional government is being imposed more by the demands of Brussels than by a genuine conviction of the political forces is beginning to be confirmed by facts.
While the new prime minister, Lukas Papadimos, warned yesterday that there is no alternative to structural reforms and that the one hundred-day period agreed upon in his appointment may be short to implement them, the leader of the conservative party New Democracy, Antonis Samaras, assured that he will not support new austerity measures in any case and reiterated his demand for new elections for the date planned, on 19 February.
"The main task of this Government is to implement the decisions of the summit of 26 October", Papadimos said as he opened a parliamentary debate yesterday that will culminate tomorrow with a vote of confidence in the new Executive.
A package of 24 programmes to boost employment, reform of the civil servants' disciplinary code and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message does not clear up any doubts about his stance: "We have committed to help the transitional government, but we have not committed to anything else".
The Conservative leader went one step further in his push for the EU and the IMF, the bodies that must unlock the 8 billion that Athens urgently needs, and made it clear that he will not give his approval to any letter of commitment to comply with the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still shocked by the impact of the Papandreou referendum, reiterated yesterday its firm demand: it will not unblock aid unless the new government and the leaders of the main Greek parties sign "an unambiguous written commitment as soon as possible".
The spokesman for Economic Affairs, Amadeu Altafaj, explained that the inspectors of the troika will return "very soon" to Athens to discuss with the new Government "what is needed to pay the sixth tranche" of 8.000 million, although there is no definitive date.
The Greek madea still has some thread for a while.
Doña Sofía: "They are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen highlights the "pre-eminent" place of Spain in relation to this type of finance
Spain "has achieved a preponderant place at the global level in the role of microfinance".
Queen Doña Sofía recalled yesterday that the country has become the second donor of the plan in relation to this instrument of cooperation, whose "essence" she noted lies in being an "instrument for social progress, justice and the hope of a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being".
The Queen opened the V World Micro-credit Summit in Valladolid yesterday with the conviction that "there is no doubt" that this type of operations are "absolutely indispensable" to achieve the Millennium Goals established by the United Nations with a 2015 horizon, and, "most especially, in the one that has as its goal the reduction to half the volume of people living with incomes below a dollar a day, with which the "poverty threshold" is set.
Spain "continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries "to all corners of the planet, and assumes this task with "responsibility", said Doña Sofía, who hoped that the initiatives and contributions that originate in the Cumbre, which will last until Thursday, "guarantee the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest, and especially for women", main beneficiaries of these loans.
It is "many achievements" and "many challenges we face".
The Microfinance Summit is not only a forum for debate but also a platform from which to push forward "two basic goals".
His Majesty explained that by the end of 2015 it is hoped that 175 million poor families will have access to these financial services and that 100 million of those households will be able to escape the poverty line.
The impetus in the conception of micro-credits in Spain and in the rest of the world "has followed the path started years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, Doña Sofía highlights as an "act of justice and due recognition".
And he described the father of this tool as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of poverty alleviation", whose work he had known for 15 years, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to get a first-hand look at her lending policy.
This experience was followed a year later by the first World Summit in Washington and other meetings such as those held in Côte d'Ivoire in 1999, Canada 2006, and "in all I have been able to see the continuous evolution", explained His Majesty, whose link with this project earned him yesterday the qualification of the "head of family" gathered in Valladolid by the "baquero of the poor".
Finally, Queen Doña Sofia concluded her speech by encouraging the audience to participate in the debate and to seek solutions to advance the fight against poverty.
'Ethical imperative'
The Minister of Foreign Affairs, Trinidad Jiménez, warned that solidarity "is an ethical imperative" for every democratic state.
He said it would be a mistake to link cooperation with developing countries in times of economic bonanza, since it is a "permanent obligation".
Jiménez considered that micro-credit is "a serious and rigorous policy to eradicate poverty", and now "more than ever" the governments of developed countries must work under solidarity criteria and not let it be a victim of cuts.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation".
For her part, Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodríguez, applauded "the success" of giving "confidence" to the people "excluded to whom all close the doors"; and the mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León de la Riva, welcomed the attendees to a city that "opens its doors contagious of the spirit of solidarity".
CDU proposes to elect the European President by universal suffrage
The first day of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) congress, held on Monday 14 November in Leipzig, was a smooth one for Angela Merkel, Chancellor and President of the Christian Democratic Party.
The future of Europe was not initially on the agenda, but the issue was imposed in the autumn, in particular to satisfy activists who consider that the government's policy is currently too lax with the Greeks and could be in the future with the Italians.
The motion on the Presidency of the European Commission, proposed by the management, was adopted almost unanimously.
Of the 1,001 delegates, only nine voted against and ten abstained.
The standing ovation of several minutes won by the speeches of Angela Merkel and, after several hours, by Wolfgang Schäuble, the Euro-friendly Finance Minister, cleared up any doubt.
The key idea of the Chancellor, and of the motion, is summed up in a slogan: the answer to the crisis is 'not less Europe, but more Europe'.
Not only because Europe means peace, but also because "nine million jobs depend directly on the euro".
For the Chancellor, "the time has come to make our way in Europe".
This could be reflected in amendments to the Lisbon Treaty to allow for stronger control of the European Union over the budgetary policies of the euro area countries, but could also lead to the election of the President of the European Commission by universal suffrage to 'give Europe a face'.
That is one of the proposals in the motion adopted by the Congress, which was clearly Wolfgang Schäuble's idea.
It is doubtful that the 27 will quickly agree on this radical change: Britain is hostile to him and the leaders of the CDU seem to know that Nicolas Sarkozy is too.
But the ball is on the ground.
The Commission has also proposed that the European Central Bank should be set up in a way which would allow the Member States to take account of the situation in the Community.
The Chancellor has been increasingly referring to Konrad Adenauer and Helmut Kohl, but she has also been anxious to calm the mood in her party, and has not been trying to win her congress at the expense of the "small" European countries or the countries in difficulty who are willing to criticize arrogant Germany.
Although the European motion has a section on the importance of 'French-German friendship', Angela Merkel has not lied to France.
Save for the pass.
