The incidence of fraud in sickness leave
After the subsidies, the UMP and the Government embark on an offensive against sick leave.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be in Bordeaux on Tuesday 15 November to visit a fund responsible for family subsidies and give a speech on the issue, which has been recurring since 2007, of fighting social fraud and aid.
Moreover, to accompany such an offensive, which starts from the will to save rigorously, but still recalls an axis of the right-wing presidential campaign, the majority wants to focus on the casualties due to illness.
Firstly, to implement budget cuts: the government plans to impose a fourth day of leave on private sector workers before they can take their leave.
In short, unless there is a specific agreement between the employer and the employee, a worker who falls ill would lose four days' pay, i.e. a minimum of 15% of his monthly earnings.
This is a measure that could raise a wave of anger, but which would allow 280 million euros to be saved, according to Les Echos.
It would also be accompanied by another measure with a more symbolic scope: imposing on civil servants a day of absence without remuneration in the event of a work stoppage (so far, they have no absence, compared to the three days applied in the private sector).
While these issues are being debated, the majority is also re-introducing the issue of fraud, this time directed towards the abuse of paychecks.
"The controls will be considerably increased and, in addition, if someone is discovered committing fraud, he will have to repay the amounts", Xavier Bertrand warned speaking on RTL on Sunday 13 November.
As in the other cases, the effects of the announcement appear to be slightly disproportionate to the reality of the strike fraud.
In fact, since 2002 this issue has been continuously monitored and various political offensives have been launched which have usually borne fruit.
The French are no more sick than the rest of Europe.
Let us look at the national figures first.
According to the French Social Security Institute (CNAM), over 237 million euros were paid in 2006 in unemployment benefits.
According to the French Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, in 2008 subsidies for deaths accounted for 5% of health expenditure, amounting to EUR 11.3 billion.
Of this sum, 46% is related to maternity and accidental leave, while 54% is related to sick leave, amounting to EUR 6.2 billion.
Hence, 2.5% of health expenditure.
In 2010, the French took an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
A mean that undoubtedly hides deviations: another survey, published in 2007 by the Syrian professional management company Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken a single day off due to illness.
Another study, in this case by Assurance maladie, shows that in 2010 37% of sick leave took less than 8 days, 22% took between 8 and 14 days, 15% took between 15 days and one month, 15% took between one and three months and 11% took longer.
If we compare them with our European neighbours, French workers are no more likely than in other areas to take sick leave.
A long study carried out in 2010 by two CNRS researchers indicated that between 1994 and 2001 the overall rate of absence from work (both for health and other reasons) ranged from 10% to 11% in France, compared with 20% to 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or between 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Fraud on sick leave is not particularly significant compared with undeclared work.
Fraud is quite limited in scope.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 has led to systematic checks on sick leave for more than 45 days.
In 2008, of 1.5 million inspections, the CNAM found that 13% of the 285,000 short-term losses were 'unjustified or too long', i.e. 37,050 cases.
In the case of losses of more than 45 days, which were subject to systematic inspections, 11% of the cases were considered to be 'properly adjusted or unjustified', a figure which, starting from a total of 1.2 million, amounts to 132,000.
Thus, a total of 169,000 cases of "unjustified" sick leave are among the several million workers who took sick leave.
This is certainly insignificant compared, for example, to the black-and-white work.
According to Dominique Tian, a member of the UMP who wrote a report on this issue in June, this practice would represent a loss of tax revenue of between EUR 9 billion and EUR 15 billion per year, i.e. more than the total cost of loss subsidies and, certainly, considerably more than fraud in this last area.
Papademos: Greece must apply a new adjustment plan
Greece is going to need a new adjustment plan to straighten its economy.
This is what Prime Minister Lucas Papademos said to Parliament on Monday 14 November, adding that the 100 days granted to his Union Government would not be enough to achieve this objective.
"To make efforts to revive the economy, we need the support of our European partners and a new budget adjustment programme", said the Head of Government, who was delivering his first public speech at the opening of the debate on the vote of confidence in Parliament on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken at the Euro Summit on 27 October will be the "main task" of the new government, since the country's permanence in the euro area is "at stake", he added.
Consequently, Papademos has forecast that the country's public deficit will be reduced "to around 9%" of GDP before the end of the year, after reaching 10.6% in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
The right rejects new austerity measures
Antonis Samaras, the head of the right-wing group, on Monday showed his support for the measures already approved to try to get out of the debt crisis, but warned that his party will not commit to additional austerity measures.
"We will not vote for new measures", he said during a meeting with the deputies of his party "New Democracy".
He said he agreed with the objectives of reducing the deficit and debt, as well as fighting waste, but against any policy that impedes economic recovery.
Mr Samaras, the European Commissioner for Economic and Monetary Affairs, told Mr Olli Rehn that the IMF and the EU would not unlock the necessary €8 billion loan without a written guarantee of all parties' support for the measures envisaged, but he replied that his word would be sufficient and that he would not sign anything because of external pressure.
A committee of experts says euthanasia and assisted suicide should be legalized
Canadians live in denial of death, says report by the Royal Society of Canada
In the field of palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just for cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
In fact, only 9 percent of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they wish to die and make arrangements for that purpose.
This is one of the conclusions of a powerful report by the Royal Society of Canada, which involved six experts from a variety of fields, including ethics, law, and medicine.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Penal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient is faced with such an option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
To begin, the experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks tenth, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death".
With or without medication, 77% of Canadians lack access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And, despite the fact that most Canadians wish to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital.
Overall, the highest rate is in Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in hospitals.
As regards the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report came to conclusions which do not coincide with the position of the Federal Government, which has already declared that it does not wish to amend the Penal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with persons who are not competent or who have not given their consent.
The report's co-author, Jocelyn Downie, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, more excesses were observed in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal".
"Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal", explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians, in favour of euthanasia
A 2010 Angus Reid poll found that 85 percent of Canadians have already spoken out in favor of euthanasia, believing that it would allow people who are about to die to ease their suffering.
Furthermore, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people are of less value.
As for people who have assisted suicide, 41% of those surveyed believe that no prosecution should be initiated against them.
The situation is not so clear, the authors of the report point out, with regard to the maintenance or interruption of health care for a patient.
In addition, among their recommendations, they suggest that it be stated in the Penal Code that withdrawal of health care, if legally refused, is not a criminal offence.
The Committee of Experts also calls for training of health professionals in the duty to respect the fact that a patient refuses assistance at the end of his life without fear of being complained about.
In the field of palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just for cancer.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health care institutions, the Committee calls for it to be considered as euthanasia and subjected to the same procedures, unless it serves to reduce physical pain.
