Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed their reservations about the conclusions of the Royal Society of Canada's expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, called the position of the experts signing the report "extreme", not least because euthanasia is not limited to terminally ill patients.
"This leaves the door open to a situation in which someone who is tired of living and is over 18 can ask for help to commit suicide", says Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value in society.
But he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations".
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" to the report's conclusions, which she called a "manifesto in favor of euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, also of the Royal Society of Canada, especially questions the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as the Netherlands and Oregon.
