Energy policy:
Facts must be worth more than dogmas.
If there is one issue that cannot be dealt with with short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of firms.
It is appropriate that an election meeting should be the time to reflect on such questions and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it looks at the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options as a whole.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are seven billion people on the planet, the demographic change will mean doubling the electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing scarcity of fossil fuels will have to be mitigated in order to continue producing electricity continuously, not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Germany therefore remains alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is obliged to find a source capable of replacing it, or in Switzerland, which is only aiming at building state-of-the-art power stations.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few, are going ahead with their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its fleet, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
The German model, based on renewable energy, is sometimes cited as an example, but the reality is quite contrary to that.
The choice of Berlin will mean higher electricity prices, greater energy dependence on the increased demand for imported gas, particularly from Russia, and increased CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal power stations.
In a few months, the damaging effects will be felt.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
Europe's champion in the wind sector, from which it obtains 30% of its electricity, it is also a major user of coal and gas due to the intermittency of wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to our consistent energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would take away the realism of the wonderful statements about the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price which the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not oppose in principle this type of energy, as polls show.
We must remember that the energy policy of our country has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Export-oriented in a broad sense, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialising in international markets and capable of creating non-locational jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of the six billion euros a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to run for 60 years, when the manufacturer is predicted to collapse?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, we must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity, just as there is no diabolical source.
The development by Areva of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France we have a safety authority which exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, with their renowned professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it caused no consequences for people or the environment.
The accident at Chernobyl was due to the design of the reactor and to unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, which caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the two previous ones.
Thanks to these developments and to cooperation between the safety authorities and the French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR is designed to withstand such phenomena.
While all the electricity players wishing to build a power station are studying it, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for Areva and EDF's competitors, since it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogma and partisan maneuvers dominate a debate so important to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a "country of human rights".
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talent, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
The point is that there is a lot of consensus on this issue between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people should not be a problem for a country with nearly two million migrant workers", while on the left, Michel Rocard set the tone by explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of a mob of Polish plumbers invading the national territory.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande merely includes banalities, indicating that co-development will solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable from an electoral point of view, but it's very expensive economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages, and employment in countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration weakens growth and hurts employment.
Fears about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, particularly the low-skilled, by pushing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that in reality immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and mainly work in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the more skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants means that the arrival of the latter has a positive influence on the salaries and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows would mean a rise in real wages in the long term of between 0,6% and 0,9%.
And, not to mention the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring to the table contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, contributing on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization, for example, estimates that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenditure) of EUR 150,000 to the public budget on average over his lifetime.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the points of growth that he was missing "with his teeth".
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it just needs to think about a European democracy
Democracy is a precious commodity, but it is also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this, because although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, it has suffered throughout the 20th century the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have thought that for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be sufficient to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that it was something thought.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had a double revealing effect in this respect: it showed the need for a powerful return to the political sphere, but also the worrying feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be reflected upon in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, the Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a disorderly manner.
A blank signature for the absolute European monarch or a stop to the nationalist hole: what choices for the citizen!
No, we do not want to make any blows, but a common exercise, full-fledged, quiet and continuous, of choice and democracy, this time on a European scale.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we wouldn't know where the list ends), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that is bending to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, the one that suffers from their impotence and their lack of solidarity.
It is Europe as a whole that is humiliated in the international arena.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is Europe as a whole which is slowly losing sovereignty and with it each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is for popular sovereignty to regain the helm of the European project.
Because only together can Europeans reduce their debt burden, free themselves from markets and prepare their future through investment.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level which cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
After a long struggle against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
So be it.
But to think of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being experienced as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and would lead us to a new stalemate.
We must enter a new phase in the construction of Europe.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The revolution motivated by interests would not be enough.
This lesson is still applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
The only way to achieve this is to build a more democratic Europe on the political level, a true European people's sovereignty.
To build Europe, let's make Europeans.
