From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-suspected links between the terrorist group Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram have been confirmed.
On Sunday, the Deputy Foreign Minister of Algeria, Abdelkader Messahel, even claimed that Algiers already "has the certainty".
"The way both organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that they are cooperating", he explained, without providing further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the runways.
Kidnapped from a restaurant in Niamey by people connected to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers have especially caught the attention of investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who stayed for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the birthplace of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly wait for more formal proof before we talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram".
"But it is possible".
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys financial and intellectual support from abroad and is becoming more active", says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such "support" has become increasingly evident in the evolution and discourses of Boko Haram or in their operational modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex suicide bombers or explosive devices in the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressuring Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long considered the group as a community of enlightened people uninteresting.
A quick hit
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which means, in Hausa, "Western education is a sin"), is pushing for the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect for sharia, while its militants launch themselves into the fight against the godless central government.
The latter are aimed primarily at churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and attacks on police stations multiplied.
Grandma's reaction was, as it often happens, widespread.
The army attacked the city and recorded 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested for life, receives death in prison.
Since then, the sect has become radicalized and abandoned its northern fiefs.
Last Christmas, he claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and then another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram attacks Abuya again, particularly the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations becomes its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would stretch from Mauritania to Somalia and Nigeria, is a matter of concern to all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and al-Shebab Somalis are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram is emerging as a new threat in the centre of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information".
