Nord Stream, new gateway for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly with Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into operation.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on the shores of the Baltic Sea, amidst orchestral music and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia with Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and their Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the flow of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
The new pipeline will bring an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas to Western Europe each year via a 1,224 km first line linking the St. Petersburg region with the Mecklenburg-Pomerania Land.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 and will supply a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, which is enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third pipe along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project looks like a victory.
Poland and the Baltic States had been strongly opposed to the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the land route through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: it will be harder for them to influence Russia by threatening to shut it off from Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting the Russian project, has achieved greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has succeeded in achieving its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, who are major gas consumers and have increasingly limited reserves, in just five years.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically", François Fillon confirmed during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which major contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of Gazprom executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the gas arrival point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of steel coated with cement to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It rests on the seabed, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid World War II minefields.
"Around 100 of them had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extend the protection measures for fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake weighing as much as 242 Eiffel Towers and is not interrupted throughout its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Swedish waters, but the project was abandoned when the Swedes were unwilling to allow a Russian state-owned company to establish itself permanently in the sea off their shores.
"In the event of a breakdown, we will stop the gas flow in less than a minute", explains Jens Müller.
In the event of a leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, since they have predicted joints that, according to forecasts, will leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the status of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, towed by a ship, which carries out external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is inserted into the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to run for fifty years without the need for any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is ensured simply by the pressure.
At first it's 200 bars and, at the output of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by E.ON and BASF of Germany (15.5% each), Gasunie of the Netherlands and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where the taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transport capacity to Gazprom for a renewable period of 25 years.
"Gazprom will pay for the full capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported", says Jens Müller.
The construction of the pipeline was financed 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach EUR 7.4 billion for the two pipes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom alone bears the risk of the expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
A few valves, 15 feet high, form the gas exit gate.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand name notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people a taste for writing.
It has an adventurous air, hours of writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular pastels, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as if aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks as they look today were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a notebook of design, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the present taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
And he succeeded.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, to reach a volume of 12,7 million units sold.
Far from it is the confidential production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer's profile, since the notebook attracts businessmen, students and professionals alike.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city centre, and has managed to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and to the need to write, despite the rise of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard caps, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that aroused envy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
Around 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week for disabled people's employment starts today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is twice the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Discouraging?
"No", says Éric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organises the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the last 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a great deal to be done".
It should be noted that the unemployed disabled continue to face numerous obstacles to access employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years old (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed their secondary education and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, longterm unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In other words, there are a number of issues which make it particularly difficult to return to work and which "are at the heart of the problem", says Christian Grapin, managing director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
There are also those that are not mentioned; people's minds move forward, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité association pointed out that the directors surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually handicapped".
The result: private enterprises with more than 20 employees are far from reaching the target of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a law of 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date back to 2008, the ratio is 2.6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, director-general of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof is that the number of establishments 'subject to this contribution', as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has put a lot of pressure on companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, particularly among the large groups".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
Hazard: "A joy to see"
Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens are about to face the Blues on Tuesday night (20:45), and they don't hide the pleasure they get from this friendly match.
We dare not say that there was any collusion between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting side by side, on the podium of the Stade de France auditorium, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have truly made peace.
Five months after his striker's gesture of resentment against Turkey, the Belgian coach has nothing but praise for him.
"I was very happy for Eden, for her progress and for being Belgian".
"I want to go forward", the Lille striker replies.
As for the contrast between his performances in his team and in the selection, "it's a set", he has justified himself.
"I'm in Lille all year round, which doesn't apply to Belgium.
"I have to get myself set".
Called to play against Romania on Friday night, in view of this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to, at last, "shine".
Not to mention the pleasure.
He has been cheering for the Blues since he was seven, as well as during the victorious campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
"I've always been a fan", he says.
This will certainly reinforce the "special" character of the meeting.
Especially because he will face "Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami) ", he recalls.
"We just faced each other a while ago.
"Playing against them is always a joy".
Leekens has made a simple reference to "pride".
"Pride" for playing "a gala game".
"Proud" also to see, as "neighbor", that France "is again a very high-level team", about a year after the trauma of Knysna.
"Laurent Blanc has done a formidable job", he said enthusiastically.
While Belgium will not be attending the next European competition, the coach would be delighted to be able to share a plane with the Blues to Brazil in 2014.
"Our little Belgians are growing", he said.
"We're building something; the players are ambitious, they're hungry.
"You'll see him in the next games". Including the game against France.
Portugal shows great confidence
Paulo Bento's Portugal is looking forward to the return match against Bosnia (22h00), which will be held on Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first game, both teams lacked realism.
"When these 90 minutes are up, we'll be a happy team and, above all, a happy country".
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
He has no doubt; the Selecçao, which he has been leading since September 2010, will qualify for the Euro 2012.
Indeed, only 90 minutes separate Portugal from happiness.
But there is one game to play and one rival, Bosnia, to beat.
Given the first leg (0-0), on Friday at Zenica Hell, it seems clear that the matter is not decided.
Portugal dominated the match for over an hour, yes, but they couldn't score the valuable goal that would have given them peace of mind.
"It's a good result, but it also carries a risk, since we haven't scored away from home".
But at home, in Lisbon's bright Stadium of Light, the Portuguese are convinced they will pass, in front of an audience that should be just as enthusiastic, even if it turns out that the match "is very even", said an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We hope the game is very level, but we are completely convinced that we can take the lead", declared the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
"We still have a 50% chance of participating in the Euro 2012", said Carlos Queiroz's successor.
Friday's draw in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
The Bosnians could get a draw, but they also need to score.
"It's a good result, but it also carries a risk, since we haven't scored outside the house", Bento laments.
"We are going to play against a team that has great technical quality and has players with great individual quality", he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will go with the intention of exerting maximum pressure on the Bosnians from the outset, so as to "not leave them time to think".
A good idea, provided it's realistic this time.
